	abstract = {The angular distribution and polarization of radiation from X-ray         bursters have been calculated. It is shown that the accretion         disc around the neutron star intercepts and re-radiates 23 per         cent of burster luminosity during a flash (28 per cent if         general relativity is taken into account). The result is a         strong dependence of radiation flux from the burster during the         flash on the inclination angle of the system. The degree of         linear polarization of burster radiation during the flash         reaches the maximum value of 3.7 per cent in the direction of         {\ensuremath{\equiv}}72.4{\textdegree} from the normal. In         periods between flashes the stationary X-radiation is provided         mainly by the boundary layer. The disc re-radiates up to 50 per         cent of the boundary-layer radiation. This results in the abrupt         variation of the stationary X-ray flux direction. The degree to         which the radiation from the system is polarized depends only         weakly on the inclination angle of the system and is about 6 per         cent.},
