	abstract = {Combing the three-dimensional radiative transfer (RT) calculation and         cosmological smoothed particle hydrodynamics (SPH) simulations,         we study the escape fraction of ionizing photons (f$_{esc}$) of         high-redshift galaxies at z= 3-6. Our simulations cover the halo         mass range of M$_{h}$= {}10$^{9}$-{}10$^{12}$ M$_{☉}$. We post-         process several hundred simulated galaxies with the Authentic         Radiative Transfer (ART) code to study the halo mass dependence         of f$_{esc}$. In this paper, we restrict ourselves to the         transfer of stellar radiation from local stellar population in         each dark matter halo. We find that the average f$_{esc}$         steeply decreases as the halo mass increases, with a large         scatter for the lower-mass haloes. The low-mass haloes with         M$_{h}${\ensuremath{\sim}} {}10$^{9}$ M$_{☉}$ have large values         of f$_{esc}$ (with an average of {\ensuremath{\sim}}0.4),         whereas the massive haloes with M$_{h}${\ensuremath{\sim}}         {}10$^{11}$ M$_{☉}$ show small values of f$_{esc}$ (with an         average of {\ensuremath{\sim}}0.07). This is because in our         simulations, the massive haloes show more clumpy structure in         gas distribution, and the star-forming regions are embedded         inside these clumps, making it more difficult for the ionizing         photons to escape. On the other hand, in low-mass haloes, there         are often conical regions of highly ionized gas due to the         shifted location of young star clusters from the centre of dark         matter halo, which allows the ionizing photons to escape more         easily than in the high-mass haloes. By counting the number of         escaped ionizing photons, we show that the star-forming galaxies         can ionize the intergalactic medium at z= 3-6. The main         contributor to the ionizing photons is the haloes with         M$_{h}${\ensuremath{\lesssim}} {}10$^{